<dl id="n53093d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53093d">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53093d"> 93(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Bedevere Butler <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53093d"><li>FW 266.10 </li><li><a href="../../flex/lb/lexlb.htm#n53093d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/lb/l39lb.htm#n53093d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53093d">MS BL 47478-332</ms> </li><li>JJA 53:311 <a name="lad13" href="../../ff/fdra/lda.htm#lbd11">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/lb/lbd11.htm#n53093d">Draft: II.2&sect;2.11</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Arthur&apos;s visit to Gaul led to a single combat between him and a man of giant stature, Flollo, &ldquo;Tribune of Rome&rdquo;; the British king was wounded in the fight, but at last &ldquo;raising Caliburn aloft&rdquo; he clove Flollo&apos;s head &ldquo;sheer in twain.&rdquo; He concluded his business in Gaul by giving &ldquo;Neustria, which is now called Normandy, unto <mark>Bedevere, his butler</mark>, and the province of Anjou unto Kay, his seneschal.&rdquo; <small> W. Lewis Jones, <a name="WJKA3" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WJKA3"><cite title="source">King Arthur in History and Legend</cite></a> (1914) 78</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Bedwyr, sometimes Bedevere, was Arthur&apos;s henchman. </mm> </dd></dl>
